The paper deals with a problem of multi-agent path finding (MAPF) and its adaptation to the token swapping problem (TSWAP). Therefore, it is likely to belong to the Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI) and Multi-Agent Systems (cs.MA) sub-categories. The paper also discusses the use of Conflict-Based Search (CBS) and Reduction to SAT (cs.DS) as approaches to solving TSWAP optimally, which suggests that it could also belong to the Data Structures and Algorithms sub-category. Additionally, the paper involves graph theory and optimization, which could place it in the Discrete Mathematics (cs.DM) sub-category. Finally, the paper presents experimental evaluation, which could indicate that it belongs to the Machine Learning (cs.LG) sub-category.
